A: You can use ObjectOutputStream to write objects to a file. When you want to read the object back, you can use ObjectInputStream.
Here is a simple example:
// Writing objects to a file
FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("objects.dat");
ObjectOutputStream out = new ObjectOutputStream(fos);

YourObject obj1 = new YourObject();
YourObject obj2 = new YourObject();

out.writeObject(obj1);
out.writeObject(obj2);

out.close();

// Reading objects from the file
FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("objects.dat");
ObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(fis);

YourObject readObj1 = (YourObject) in.readObject();
YourObject readObj2 = (YourObject) in.readObject();

in.close();

In this example, replace "YourObject" with the class name of the objects you want to write to the file.
If you want to read the objects from a random access file, you can seek to the correct position in the file before reading the object. Here is an example:
RandomAccessFile raf = new RandomAccessFile("objects.dat", "rw");

// Seek to the position where the object is written
raf.seek(position);

// Read the object
YourObject obj = (YourObject) new ObjectInputStream(raf).readObject();

Note that the position is the byte offset from the beginning of the file. You need to keep track of the positions where you write the objects to the file.
Also, remember that the objects you write to the file must implement the Serializable interface.

